00:00:55.400 --> 00:00:58.980
In 1902, Harris Weinstock,
a well-known businessman

00:00:58.980 --> 00:01:02.040
of Sacramento presented the
University of California

00:01:02.040 --> 00:01:04.940
with a fund to support
an annual public lecture

00:01:04.940 --> 00:01:08.253
on the morals of trade on
behalf of his wife, Barbara.

00:01:09.220 --> 00:01:11.070
Weinstock was fundamentally committed

00:01:11.070 --> 00:01:14.030
to the economic and moral
progress of humankind.

00:01:14.030 --> 00:01:15.750
He wrote many newspaper columns

00:01:15.750 --> 00:01:18.000
and gave numerous lectures on topics

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:21.160
ranging from Napoleon to socialism.

00:01:21.160 --> 00:01:24.130
Inspired by Spencer and Newton's essays

00:01:24.130 --> 00:01:25.600
on the morals of trade

00:01:25.600 --> 00:01:27.210
which lamented the state of morals

00:01:27.210 --> 00:01:30.210
in the mid 19th century business world

00:01:30.210 --> 00:01:32.420
he argued that a man does not profit

00:01:32.420 --> 00:01:33.810
if he gains the whole world

00:01:33.810 --> 00:01:35.163
and loses his soul.

00:01:36.660 --> 00:01:39.150
Harris Weinstock hoped
that this lectureship

00:01:39.150 --> 00:01:40.900
would lead to a better life for those

00:01:40.900 --> 00:01:43.900
who spent their lives
in commercial pursuits.

00:01:43.900 --> 00:01:45.857
He said, and I quote,

00:01:45.857 --> 00:01:48.067
"Let men and women the world over

00:01:48.067 --> 00:01:50.877
"worship character rather than wealth.

00:01:50.877 --> 00:01:53.737
"Let them do homage to the high-minded

00:01:53.737 --> 00:01:57.357
"and pure-minded rather than
the merely rich and powerful.

00:01:57.357 --> 00:01:59.687
"And the ideal age will be at hand

00:01:59.687 --> 00:02:02.497
"when trade will carry
with it the badge of honor

00:02:02.497 --> 00:02:04.417
"and the successful man of business

00:02:04.417 --> 00:02:07.297
"will take the high
place hitherto confined

00:02:07.297 --> 00:02:10.880
"to the patriot and faithful
servant of mankind."

00:02:10.880 --> 00:02:11.713
End quote.

00:02:12.610 --> 00:02:14.040
Past lecturers who have delivered

00:02:14.040 --> 00:02:15.920
the Barbara Weinstock Memorial Lectures

00:02:15.920 --> 00:02:17.980
on the Morals of Trade include;

00:02:17.980 --> 00:02:19.270
Ralph Nader,

00:02:19.270 --> 00:02:21.380
member of Parliament, Neil Kinnock

00:02:21.380 --> 00:02:23.593
and Nobel Laureate Amartya Sen.

